        "header": "1Introduction",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.09095/2603.09095v1/x1.png",
                "caption": "Figure 1:Humans read text through vision from diverse sources such as books, webpages, and documents, whereas MLLMs may yield different predictions when the same textual content is presented in different input forms.",
                "position": 308
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.09095/2603.09095v1/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:Diagnosing the modality gap in visual text understanding.\nWe evaluate MLLMs across five input modes, including pure text, rendered text images, real-world visual text, and two OCR-based diagnostic settings (OCR-1PandOCR-2P).\nOur error taxonomy reveals that while image modality amplifies reading and calculation errors, it leaves underlying reasoning capabilities largely intact but also reduces the likelihood of triggering a reasoning chain.\nWe further propose remedies to bridge the performance gap, including rendering specification control, resolution-aware preprocessing, and LM-only self-distillation.",
                "position": 312
            }
        ]
    },
